      <text>
        The first hour set the pattern for everything that followed. Rootwalker walked ahead, each step methodical and grounded — not fast but relentless, a pace that looked easy and somehow covered ground. I follow, Scout bouncing alongside me, Buddy humming softly from my pocket.

        Leafwhisper said, "So this is the old growth section I mentioned earlier — absolutely beautiful, isn't it? The canopy here is at least two hundred years established, which means the mycorrhizal networks are incredibly dense and mature — you can actually feel the information flow if you're connected properly, though I suppose humans don't have that same ground connection — very different sensory experience, I imagine — oh, look, see those vines to the left? Those are Reaching type — they communicate through touch like Runner did back at the facility, but these ones are specialized for vertical growth — fascinating adaptation, really —"

        The leaves rustled continuously, producing rapid cascading speech that jumped from observation to observation without pause.

        ¶

        I try to keep up at first — actually process the information being shared — but the volume is overwhelming.

        Leafwhisper continued, "And the soil composition here transitions from loam to more clay-based about fifty meters ahead, which you'll notice affects the plant species distribution — more moisture-retentive substrates support different fungal communities, which then influences the entire local network architecture —"

        Rootwalker's deep voice cut through the cascade. Rootwalker said, "Root crossing."

        Leafwhisper exclaimed, "Oh yes! Exactly what I was getting to! See how the path navigates around that large root system? Very important for human balance — center of gravity issues, like I mentioned — you'll want to step carefully here, to Kira —"

        I step over the prominent root, carefully.

        Scout bounces ahead, clearly enjoying the new terrain. The little plant seems energized by travel — investigating interesting features, rolling back to check on me, then bouncing forward again.

        Leafwhisper observed, "Your Scout companion is adapting wonderfully to the journey! Very mobile species, excellent travel disposition — I've guided a few sphere-type plants before and they're always such pleasant companions, very self-sufficient, don't require much support, though I notice Scout stays close to you which suggests strong attachment formation —"

        I ask, "How far today?"

        Leafwhisper rustled enthusiastically, "Approximately twenty-three kilometers! Which sounds like a lot but it's a very manageable pace — we'll take regular rest breaks of course, every two hours recommended for bipedal travelers to prevent fatigue accumulation, and Rootwalker knows all the best spots with good ground stability and access to water sources —"

        "Twenty-three kilometers," I repeat — about fourteen miles. That is… a lot of walking.
      </text>
