        Leafwhisper assured me, "That's very normal! Humans have excellent endurance actually, much better than many species, but it requires conditioning and you've been stationary for the past week while healing — perfectly reasonable to feel fatigue at this stage —"

        Rootwalker had moved to the spring and returned a moment later with water cupped in their root hands, offering it to me. The gesture surprises me — quiet care delivered without words.

        I say, "Thank you."

        Rootwalker just nodded and moved away to check the path ahead.

        Leafwhisper said more quietly, "Rootwalker is very good at anticipating needs — doesn't talk much but always pays attention, excellent guide really, we've worked together for many journeys and I've learned to read their actions — when they stop suddenly it means obstacle ahead, when they adjust pace it means terrain difficulty changing — very reliable communication once you learn the patterns —"

        I drink the cool water and try to imagine several more days of this — constant walking, Leafwhisper's constant talking, Rootwalker's constant silence.

        It should be exhausting — it kind of is exhausting.

        But there is something nice about it too: being part of a team, having guides who know what they're doing, not having to make every decision or solve every problem myself.

        Buddy said softly to Kira, "Your heart rate and respiration are within normal exercise parameters. Leg tissue showing no stress indicators. You're doing well."

        I say, "Thanks, Buddy."

        Buddy continued, "Though I should mention you'll likely experience significant muscle soreness tomorrow! Human bodies adapt to new movement patterns through microtrauma and repair, it's quite fascinating really —"

        *Leafwhisper chimed in*, "Buddy's absolutely right! The adaptation process is wonderful — by day three you'll notice significant improvement in stamina and efficiency, humans are remarkably good at physical conditioning when given appropriate stimulus and recovery time —"

        Rootwalker returned and said, "Time."

        They'd rested maybe fifteen minutes.

        ¶

        I stand. My legs protest slightly, but not unbearably.

        *Leafwhisper rustled*, "Back to it then! The next section goes through a particularly beautiful grove where the light filters through in these amazing patterns, you're going to love it — well I think you will — hard to know exactly what humans find aesthetically pleasing but the biomechanical efficiency is remarkable and often organisms appreciate functional beauty —"

        They walked.

        The afternoon blurred into rhythm. Step, step, step.

        Leafwhisper's running commentary covered everything — plants, terrain, network protocols, interesting rocks, that one moss species, the way this particular fern reproduced, optimal photosynthesis angles, historical route changes, weather pattern effects.

        Rootwalker occasionally interjected, "Left here." — "Root system." — "Slow." — "Rest soon."

        Scout explored and returned, explored and returned — endless energy.
      </text>
