        And I walk, just walk, following Rootwalker's steady pace — half-listening to Leafwhisper's cascade of information, letting the forest happen around me instead of trying to control or understand everything.

        It is different from the facility, different from those first desperate days — this is… purposeful, moving toward something, making progress.

        When they stop for the second rest, my legs are definitely complaining.

        I ask, "How much further?"

        Leafwhisper says, "About seven more kilometers! You're doing wonderfully by the way — excellent pace maintenance — many first-time travelers struggle more than this on day one — very impressive endurance—"

        Seven kilometers — four more miles. She could do four more miles.

        I ask, "When we stop for the night, there'll be food?"

        Leafwhisper says, "Absolutely! I can synthesize the mushroom compounds you require — already have the protocols from your dietary documentation — won't be quite as sophisticated as Remedy's work but nutritionally complete and perfectly edible—"

        I say, "It'll be fine — mushroom paste is mushroom paste."

        Leafwhisper says, "Practical attitude! Very helpful for long journeys!"

        Rootwalker stands and says, "Time."

        The final stretch is hard — my feet hurt, my legs burn, my back aches from the unfamiliar pack weight.

        But the sun is setting — or whatever this planet's star does — painting the canopy in shades of purple and gold, and Rootwalker is leading us somewhere specific.

        We reach it just as the bioluminescence starts brightening.

        A rest shelter — smaller than the facility but functional — woven plant structures creating walls and roof, moss beds inside, a water feature, even a small clearing where mushrooms are already fruiting.

        Leafwhisper says, "And here we are! End of day one — approximately twenty-three point seven kilometers traveled — excellent performance really — you should be very proud—"

        I collapse onto the moss bed.

        ¶

        Scout settles next to me, unusually quiet.

        I ask the little plant, "Tired?"

        Scout bounces once — gently — definitely tired.

        I say, "Me too."

        While Leafwhisper synthesizes dinner — still chatting about nutrient profiles and synthesis efficiency — Rootwalker checks the shelter, reinforces a few structural points, ensures the water flow is clean.

        Quiet, competent care.

        When Leafwhisper brings the food — predictable gray mushroom paste — I eat gratefully; my body needs fuel.

        Leafwhisper says, "Tomorrow will be easier — your muscles will be sore initially but the body adapts quickly — we'll maintain similar pace so it won't feel as challenging—"

        I ask, "How do you two work together? You're so… different."
      </text>
